Classification.Comment: The copy number gain of 2q11.1q13 involves 129 protein-coding genes. Duplications of single or multiple cytobands from 2q11.1 to 2q13 have been reported in numerous cases of patients with neurological, gastrointestinal, and congenital anomalies (Aarabi 2022, Riley 2015, Rudd 2009, Chen 2020). Rudd et al. (2009), however, did suggest that duplications of 2q13 may demonstrate reduced penetrance based on observations in phenotypically normal individuals. There are no similar copy number gains of this region in the general populations of the Database of Genomic Variants. Thus, based on current medical literature and gene content, this copy number variant (CNV) is classified as pathogenic. References: Aarabi et al., Psychiatr Genet. 2022 Jul 15. PMID: 35837682 Chen et al., Taiwan J Obstet Gynecol. 2020 Nov;59(6):941-944. PMID: 33218417 Riley et al., Am J Med Genet A. 2015 Nov;167A(11):2664-73. PMID: 26227573 Rudd et al., Hum Mol Genet. 2009 Aug 15;18(16):2957-62. PMID: 19443486
